  "prompt": "If you were born deaf, what language would you think in?",
  "response": "If you were born deaf, the language you think in would depend on the language you were exposed to and learned as you grew up. For many deaf individuals, this would be a signed language, such as American Sign Language (ASL) in the United States, British Sign Language (BSL) in the UK, or another signed language depending on the country and culture. \n\nSigned languages are complete, natural languages with their own grammar, syntax, and vocabulary, and they are fully capable of expressing complex thoughts and emotions. Therefore, a deaf person who learned a signed language from a young age would likely think in that signed language.\n\nIf a deaf person was taught a spoken/written language (like English, Spanish, etc.) through visual or tactile methods, they might also think in that language, especially if they use it frequently for reading, writing, or communication.\n\nIn some cases, deaf individuals might think in a combination of signed and written languages, depending on their experiences and the contexts in which they use each language.",
